[start section id="20103"]

I have been asked by Dr. White's service to visit with Ms. Mingo for postoperative education purposes.  Briefly, Ms. Mingo is a very pleasant 69-year-old female from Keota Wellston.  She has a complicated past medical history significant for severe COPD, endocarditis, bioprosthetic St. Jude mitral valve repair, on chronic anticoagulation due to rheumatic heart disease, pacemaker implantation and status-post CABG, and chronic lymphocytic leukemia, currently stable.
1.  September 30, 2010 - underwent colonoscopy identifying a mass at 50 cm.  Partially removed by polypectomy.  Biopsies confirmed adenocarcinoma.
2.  October 6, 2010 - developed abdominal pain.  Noted on imaging to have pneumoperitoneum due to perforated colon during colonoscopy.  CT imaging done without contrast due to an allergy showed a thickening of the gallbladder wall.  No evidence of distant disease.
3.  October 22, 2010 - taken by Dr. White for resection of a portion of the transverse colon and open cholecystectomy.  Surgical pathology from the colon identifying a mildly-differentiated grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a-1.1-cm x 0.9-cm x 0.4-cm ulcerated mass in the transverse colon superficially invading the muscularis propria.  Negative surgical margins, and 5 regional lymph nodes negative for tumor.  Staged at a T2, N0, M0.  Gallbladder cholecystectomy showing an adenomyoma 2.2-cm x 1.7-cm x 1.5-cm in size in the fundus of the gallbladder.  No evidence of distant disease.
Ms. Mingo is continuing to recover from surgery and was currently up sitting in bed during our consultation today.

